<emphasis box="[222,422,1636,1655]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="3862">Peraeospinosus magnus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kudinova-Pasternak RK" box="[436,691,1636,1655]" pageId="16" pageNumber="3862" pagination="90 - 107" refId="ref18989" refString="Kudinova-Pasternak RK. 1990. Tanaidacea (Crustacea, Malacostraca) of the southeastern part of Atlantic Ocean and the region to the north off Mordvinov (Elephant) Island. Trudy Instituta Okeanologii, Akademiya Nauk SSSR 126: 90 - 107." type="journal article" year="1990">Kudinova-Pasternak, 1990</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, holotype female (MS-9). (A) Female dorsal view; (B) antennule; (C) antenna; (D) pleopod; (E) uropod. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A); 0.1 mm (B–E).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,1185,185,339]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,225,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Female.</emphasis>
Carapace 1.25 times longer than wide, truncated anteriorly. Pereonites 1, 2, and 4–6 wider than long. Pereonite 1 relatively long (two-thirds length of carapace). Pleon longer than carapace; pleotelson truncated posteriorly. Antennule article 3 three times as long as article 2. Pleopod endopod with two dorsal setae. Uropod rami subequal.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,421,396,420]" box="[138,421,396,420]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,421,396,420]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Supplementary description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,780,445,469]" box="[138,780,445,469]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
Female without oostegites, length 
<quantity box="[541,628,445,469]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863" unit="mm" value="6.1">6.1 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[645,767,445,469]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="16.[125,185,1636,1655]" captionTargetBox="[129,1172,190,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-0@16.[125,1173,181,1600]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 6. Peraeospinosus magnus (Kudinova-Pasternak, 1990), holotype female (MS-9). (A) Female dorsal view; (B) antennule; (C) antenna; (D) pleopod; (E) uropod. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A); 0.1 mm (B–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221072/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Figure 6A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,807,510,534]" box="[138,807,510,534]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,204,510,534]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Body.</emphasis>
Body about seven to eight times longer than wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,1185,574,663]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,416,574,598]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Pereonites and pleonites.</emphasis>
Pereon 1 is two-thirds as long as carapace and subequal to pereonite 6; pleon longer than carapace; all pleonites similar in size; pleotelson truncated posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,1185,704,825]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,402,704,728]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
Antennule (
<figureCitation box="[271,388,704,728]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="16.[125,185,1636,1655]" captionTargetBox="[129,1172,190,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-0@16.[125,1173,181,1600]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 6. Peraeospinosus magnus (Kudinova-Pasternak, 1990), holotype female (MS-9). (A) Female dorsal view; (B) antennule; (C) antenna; (D) pleopod; (E) uropod. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A); 0.1 mm (B–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221072/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Figure 6B</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Article 1 a little longer than articles 2 and 3 combined, with three pinnate setae distally and three minute setae along article; article 2 is one-third as long as article 3, with one simple seta distally; article 3 with seven simple apical setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,1185,866,955]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,378,866,890]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[248,365,866,890]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="16.[125,185,1636,1655]" captionTargetBox="[129,1172,190,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-0@16.[125,1173,181,1600]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 6. Peraeospinosus magnus (Kudinova-Pasternak, 1990), holotype female (MS-9). (A) Female dorsal view; (B) antennule; (C) antenna; (D) pleopod; (E) uropod. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A); 0.1 mm (B–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221072/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Figure 6C</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Article 2 twice as long as article 3, both with short rod seta; article 4 twice as long as article 5, with five setae distally; article 5 with one simple seta distally; article 6 very short, with seven terminal setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,555,996,1020]" box="[138,555,996,1020]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,443,996,1020]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Mouth parts and pereopods.</emphasis>
Missing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,1185,1061,1182]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,381,1061,1085]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
Pleopods (
<figureCitation box="[249,368,1061,1085]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="16.[125,185,1636,1655]" captionTargetBox="[129,1172,190,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-0@16.[125,1173,181,1600]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 6. Peraeospinosus magnus (Kudinova-Pasternak, 1990), holotype female (MS-9). (A) Female dorsal view; (B) antennule; (C) antenna; (D) pleopod; (E) uropod. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A); 0.1 mm (B–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221072/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Figure 6D</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
All pleopods similar in structure; endopod with two dorsal (inner) setae, exopod and endopod with a row of plumose setae on outer margin (length: width ratio of exopod 3.75; of endopod 2.9); no clear gap between the most proximal and other setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,1185,1223,1311]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,362,1223,1247]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
Uropod (
<figureCitation box="[232,348,1223,1247]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="16.[125,185,1636,1655]" captionTargetBox="[129,1172,190,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-0@16.[125,1173,181,1600]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 6. Peraeospinosus magnus (Kudinova-Pasternak, 1990), holotype female (MS-9). (A) Female dorsal view; (B) antennule; (C) antenna; (D) pleopod; (E) uropod. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A); 0.1 mm (B–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221072/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Figure 6E</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Both rami uni-articled, subequal; endopod with one pinnate seta at the middle, tipped by four simple terminal setae and three pinnate setae; exopod with short simple middle seta on outer margin, tipped by strong and minute simple seta.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,267,1381,1405]" box="[138,267,1381,1405]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,267,1381,1405]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,688,1430,1454]" box="[138,688,1430,1454]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[401,450,1430,1454]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<figureCitation box="[558,675,1430,1454]" captionStart="Figure 25" captionStartId="52.[125,185,926,945]" captionTargetBox="[128,1172,136,890]" captionTargetId="figure-184@52.[125,1173,133,890]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="Figure 25. Distribution of genus Peraeospinosus based on Beddard (1886a, 1886b), Kudinova-Pasternak (1966, 1969, 1990), Lang (1968), and Shiino (1978)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221119" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221119/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Figure 25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,233,1511,1535]" box="[138,233,1511,1535]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<emphasis box="[138,233,1511,1535]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[138,1185,1560,1681]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Błażewicz-Paszkowycz" authorityYear="2005" baseAuthorityName="Kudinova-Pasternak" baseAuthorityYear="1990" box="[138,393,1560,1584]" class="Malacostraca" family="Typhlotanaidae" genus="Peraeospinosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnus">
<emphasis box="[138,393,1560,1584]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Peraeospinosus magnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[709,813,1560,1584]" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">holotype</typeStatus>
, a specimen which lacks most appendages. The combination of characters observed in the antennule, antennae, pleopods, and uropods is enough to recognize 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Błażewicz-Paszkowycz" authorityYear="2005" baseAuthorityName="Kudinova-Pasternak" baseAuthorityYear="1990" box="[690,807,1625,1648]" class="Malacostraca" family="Typhlotanaidae" genus="Peraeospinosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnus">
<emphasis box="[690,807,1625,1648]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">P. magnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species. It is the only member of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sieg" authorityYear="1986" box="[275,434,1657,1681]" class="Malacostraca" family="Typhlotanaidae" genus="Peraeospinosus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[275,434,1657,1681]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="3863">Peraeospinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with two setae on the inner margin of the pleopods.
</paragraph>
